Finance Data Project¶

In this data project we will focus on Data Wrangling and EDA of stock prices for data trading dataset by daytrader.ai, https://www.kaggle.com/daytrader/ema-65-crossover

Link to Github repo for this file: https://github.com/gaurav214/Udacity-DataScience

Link to blog post for this project: https://medium.com/@negi.gaurav2/stock-price-analysis-afc61ebdcde1

This project will include an analysis of best stocks for day trading¶

The NASDAQ stock market is an American stock exchange. It is the second largest exchange in the world by market capitalization, behind only New York Stock Exchange located in the same city. The exchange platform is owned by Nasdaq.Inc

In this post, we will analyse 3 years of NASDAQ100 data (from 2014 to mid 2017). This data set includes stock prices for following companies:

FB — Facebook
GOOG — Google class C
AAPL — Apple
TSLA — Tesla
MSFT — Microsoft
NVDA — NVidia
AMZN — Amazon
CRM — Salesforce
GOOGL — Google class A
ADBE — Adobe
NFLX — Netflix
INTC — Intel
BIDU — Bai

The following piece of code will combine the data of similar companies from more than 17,000 csv files¶

In [91]:
def combine_data(indir,outfile,company):
    """ 
    The following code will combine all the data from the files in the folder for similar companies.
    
    Parameters:
    indir: Input directory
    outfile: Output directory
    
    """
    os.chdir(indir)
    filelist = glob.glob(company)
    dflist = []
    colnames = ['ISO formatted date', 'closing price', 'volume']
    for filename in filelist:
#        print(filename)
        df = pd.read_csv(filename,header = None)
        dflist.append(df)
    
    
    concatDf = pd.concat(dflist,axis=0)
    concatDf.columns = colnames
    concatDf.to_csv(outfile,index =None)

# This code will remove duplicates and arrange the price in ascending order 
def remove_duplicates(filename,outfile):
    
    """ 
    The following code will remove all duplicate values and arrange the price in ascending order.
    
    Parameters:
    filename: Old file directory.
    outfile: New File directory.
    
    """
    
    df = pd.read_csv(filename)
    df.drop_duplicates(subset=['ISO formatted date'], keep='first', inplace=True)
    df = df.sort_values(by='ISO formatted date')
    df.to_csv(outfile,index = False)

EDA¶

Question 1: What is the maximum closing price of each stock?¶

Business Understading: The closing price is the final price at which a security is traded on a given trading day. The closing price represents the most up-to-date valuation of a security until trading commences again on the next trading day. Here we want to find at what time-stamp each company hit the maximum closing price of their stock.

Data Understanding: We have data of 12 companies stock price for over 3 years(2014 to 2017). The stock prices are stored every minute to get best granularity for our analysis. Initially we started with stock prices for each company and then denormalized all the companies stocks data into one data set. This helped in comparison between all stocks and improve our read performance.

Data Preparation: All the dataframes of companies were combined to a single dataset and then after combining all the stock prices of companies we did group by search for maximum closing price of each company and this what we observed.

Results:

Question 2: Which stocks have highly correlated returns?¶

Business Understanding: In finance, return is a profit on an investment. It comprises any change in value of the investment, and/or cash flows which the investor receives from the investment, such as interest payments or dividends. It may be measured either in absolute terms (e.g., dollars) or as a percentage of the amount invested. Here we want to find the stocks that are highly correlated and might help a day trader to predict the behaviour of one stock by observing the behaviour of other stock.

Data Understanding:Our prepared data set include 13 columns with first column being the timestamp of a specific stock price and all other 12 columns represent the stock price of their respective company.

Data Prepration: We created a new empty DataFrame called returns. This dataframe will contain the returns for each stock. returns are typically defined by:**

$$r_t = \frac{p_t - p_{t-1}}{p_{t-1}} = \frac{p_t}{p_{t-1}} - 1$$

We also used pandas pct_change() method on the Close column to create a column representing this return value. Create a for loop that goes and for each Stock column and creates this returns column and set's it as a column in the returns DataFrame.

Question 3: Which stock would you classify as the riskiest over the entire time period?¶

Business Understanding:

The risk of the stock is determined by the how much the stock price varies within a period of time. Here we want to find out the company with very unstable price growth and the company which is the least riskiest to invest in. This use case will help a day trader to sort the stocks by their risk factor and help in making effective day trading strategies.

Data Understanding:

Standard deviation is a quantity expressing by how much the members of a group differ from the mean value for the group. In our dataset we are taking standard deviation of each company stock and then comparing them to determine which stocks differ by how much.

Results Evaluations:

Netflix is the most risky stock as it has the highest standard deviation of 0.002457 and Adobe is the least risky stock with a standard deviation of 0.001222. Netflix has a gradually increasing but very fluctuating graph(high standard deviation) and Adobe with the most stable growth and least standard deviation.
